                <fr:title text="an alternative definition of duploids">an alternative definition of duploids</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Observation</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Equivalently, we can define a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0050.xml" title="duploid" addr="jms-0050" type="local">duploid</fr:link> to be a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004T.xml" title="univalent deductive system" addr="jms-004T" type="local">univalent</fr:link> <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004F.xml" title="preduploid" addr="jms-004F" type="local">preduploid</fr:link> such that every object is <html:em>merely equipped with</html:em> both an <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004M.xml" title="upshift structure" addr="jms-004M" type="local">upshift</fr:link> and a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004P.xml" title="downshift structure" addr="jms-004P" type="local">downshift</fr:link>.</html:p><html:p>To see that the <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0050.xml" title="duploid" addr="jms-0050" type="local">main definition</fr:link> implies our alternative definition, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> be an object of the preduploid; because we are proving that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <html:em>merely equipped with</html:em> both an <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004M.xml" title="upshift structure" addr="jms-004M" type="local">upshift</fr:link> and a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004P.xml" title="downshift structure" addr="jms-004P" type="local">downshift</fr:link>, we may proceed by cases on the <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0045.xml" title="polarized object" addr="jms-0045" type="local">polarization</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:ol><html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004B.xml" title="positive and negative objects" addr="jms-004B" type="local">positive</fr:link>, we choose the identity map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\vdash  A]]></fr:tex> for the downshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has an upshift.</html:li>
  <html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004B.xml" title="positive and negative objects" addr="jms-004B" type="local">negative</fr:link>, we choose the identity map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\vdash  A]]></fr:tex> for the upshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has a downshift.</html:li></html:ol>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:addr>jms-0051/0</fr:addr><fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0051/0.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="an alternative definition of duploids › forest://jonmsterling/jms-0051/0"><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0051.xml" title="an alternative definition of duploids" addr="jms-0051" type="local">an alternative definition of duploids</fr:link> › jms-0051/0</fr:title><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>Conversely, assume that every object is merely equipped with both an upshift and a downshift. That a positive object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> has an upshift <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004X.xml" title="uniqueness of upshifts" addr="jms-004X" type="local">is a proposition</fr:link>, so we can use our assumption that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> <html:em>merely</html:em> has an upshift. That a negative object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> has a downshift <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-004Z.xml" title="uniqueness of downshifts" addr="jms-004Z" type="local">is likewise a proposition</fr:link>, so we can use our assumption that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> <html:em>merely</html:em> has a downshift.</html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
